excerpt: Old-world Intramuros is home to Spanish-era landmarks like Fort Santiago, with a large stone gate and a shrine to national hero José Rizal. The ornate Manila Cathedral houses bronze carvings and stained glass windows, while the San Agustin Church museum has religious artwork and statues. Spanish colonial furniture and art fill Casa Manila museum, and horse-drawn carriages (kalesa) ply the area’s cobblestone streets.
detail_description: Intramuros, meaning "within the walls," is Manila's oldest neighborhood and historic heart. Built by the Spanish in the late 16th century, it has been a center of government, culture, and trade for over 350 years. Despite damage from wars and natural disasters, recent restoration efforts have preserved its colonial architecture.
name: Intramuros
address: Manila, 1002 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: This landmark defensive fortress features a museum commemorating the national hero José Rizal.
detail_description: Fort Santiago is a historic defensive fortress located in Manila, Philippines. It was originally constructed in 1590 by Spanish conquistadors on the site of a pre-Hispanic king's palace. The fortress has been restored and now serves as a museum and public park within the Intramuros district. One of its main attractions is the Rizal Shrine, dedicated to national hero José Rizal who was imprisoned there before his execution in 1896.
name: Fort Santiago
address: Intramuros, Manila, 1002 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Grand 57-hectare park featuring lawns, gardens, outdoor events & a monument to hero José Rizal.
detail_description: Rizal Park, also known as Luneta Park, is a sprawling 57-hectare urban park located in the heart of Manila. It is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike, offering lush lawns, vibrant gardens, and outdoor event spaces. The park is an ideal spot for picnics with its shady trees and expansive grassy areas.
name: Rizal Park
address: Ermita, Manila, 1000 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Binondo is a district in Manila and is referred to as the city's Chinatown. Its influence extends beyond to the places of Quiapo, Santa Cruz, San Nicolas and Tondo. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Binondo, also known as Manila's Chinatown, is a historic district in Manila and is considered the oldest Chinatown in the world. The name "Binondo" comes from the Tagalog word "binondoc," which means mountainous. Originally established for Chinese immigrants who converted to Catholicism, it has evolved into a bustling community with vibrant shopping streets and renowned restaurants serving authentic Chinese cuisine such as Peking duck and dumplings.
name: Binondo
address: Manila, 1006 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Historic church constructed starting in the 16th century with vaulted ceilings & detailed frescoes.
detail_description: The Archdiocesan Shrine of Our Lady of Consolation and Cincture, also known as San Agustin Church, is a historic church in Manila. Constructed in the 16th century, it features vaulted ceilings and detailed frescoes. It is one of the oldest churches in the Philippines and survived the Battle of Manila during World War II. Designated as a National Historical Landmark by the Philippine government and a UNESCO World Heritage Site, it holds significant historical value.
name: San Agustin Church
address: General Luna St, Intramuros, Manila, 1002 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Aquatic theme park & educational facility featuring hands-on activities, an oceanarium & live shows.
detail_description: Manila Ocean Park is a must-visit aquatic theme park and educational facility in Manila. It offers hands-on activities, an oceanarium with over 14,000 aquatic creatures from 270 species, including sharks, stingrays, jellyfish, and the first penguin facility in the country. The park also features live shows, exhibits, and an amusement park area. It's a great place for families to explore and learn about marine life while enjoying entertaining experiences.
name: Manila Ocean Park
address: 666 Behind, Quirino Grandstand, Ermita, City Of Manila, 1000 Metro Manila, Philippines

detail_description: Star City is a well-known amusement park in Pasay that offers an exciting mix of thrilling rides and entertaining attractions suitable for all ages. The park features a variety of experiences, from adrenaline-pumping roller coasters to family-friendly carousels, ensuring there's something for everyone. In addition to the rides, visitors can enjoy live shows, game stalls, and delicious dining options. It's a perfect destination for a fun-filled day out with loved ones.
name: Star City
address: Roxas Blvd, CCP, Pasay City, 1300 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Built in 1571, this historic church is known for its ornate architecture & visits by several popes.
detail_description: The Minor Basilica and Metropolitan Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception, also known as Manila Cathedral, is a historic church with ornate architecture dating back to 1571. It has been visited by several popes and is considered the Mother of all churches in the Philippines. The cathedral's Neo-Romanesque design, solemn ambiance, priceless relics, and stained glass windows make it a must-visit for both locals and tourists.
name: Minor Basilica and Metropolitan Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception - The Manila Cathedral
address: Cabildo, 132 Beaterio St, Intramuros, Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Massive museum with collections of Filipino fine art, archaeology, botany, natural history & more.
detail_description: The National Museum of Fine Arts is a significant cultural institution in the Philippines, showcasing an extensive collection of Filipino fine art, archaeology, botany, and natural history. As a government trust, it is dedicated to acquiring, preserving, and exhibiting works of art and historical artifacts that represent the rich cultural heritage of the Filipino people. The museum complex includes regional museums across the country and features renowned pieces such as the Spoliarium by Juan Luna.
name: National Museum of Fine Arts
address: Padre Burgos Ave, Ermita, Manila, 1000 Metro Manila, Philippines

detail_description: Quiapo Church, like many other religious sites in Manila, has endured natural disasters and conflicts throughout its history. Despite these challenges, the church has maintained its Baroque facade featuring a grand pediment, twin towers, and Corinthian columns. However, visitors may be surprised by the modern interior with its sleek white design dating back to the 1980s.
name: Quiapo Church City Plaza
address: Church, Plaza, Miranda, Quiapo, City Of Manila, 1001 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: This restored 1850s house is now a museum displaying Spanish colonial furniture, art & architecture.
detail_description: Casa Manila, a meticulously restored 1850s house turned museum, offers a glimpse into the opulent lifestyle of a wealthy Filipino family during the late Spanish colonial era. The facade is inspired by an actual residence from Binondo's Chinese district, while the interior showcases lavish European and Chinese furniture, crystal chandeliers, painted walls, and gilded furnishings that defined Manila houses of that period.
name: Casa Manila
address: plaza sans luis complex, General Luna St, Intramuros, Manila, 1002 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Modern museum for Filipino archeological artifacts, history & culture exhibits & a research library.
detail_description: Located in Makati, the Ayala Museum is a modern museum housed in a former stock exchange building. It showcases Filipino archaeological artifacts, history, and culture through six main permanent exhibitions. Visitors can explore traditional maritime vessels, embroidered silk garments from the 19th century elite, Chinese porcelain reflecting centuries of trade, and artworks by renowned Filipino artists like Fernando Zobel and Juan Luna.
name: Ayala Museum
address: Makati Avenue, corner Dela Rosa Street, Ayala Center, Makati City, 1229 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Old downtown street established in 1594, with art deco buildings, pop-up shops & cafes.
detail_description: Escolta St, established in 1594, is one of Manila's oldest streets. It was once the heart of the city's Central Business District and home to the Manila Stock Exchange. While many businesses have moved, Escolta still boasts impressive art deco buildings like Regina Building and Capitol Theater. The street got its name from Spanish word for 'escort' during the British occupation when military escorts would pass through.
name: Escolta St
address: Manila, Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Sprawling shopping complex around a leafy garden & ponds, with eateries & movie theaters.
detail_description: Greenbelt is a sprawling shopping complex nestled around a lush garden and serene ponds, offering an array of eateries and movie theaters. The Santo Nino de Paz, also known as the Greenbelt Chapel, is a stunning hidden gem within the mall, featuring a distinctive low dome shape and surrounded by water and greenery.
name: Greenbelt
address: Legazpi Street, Legazpi Village, Makati City, Metro Manila, Philippines

detail_description: Baywalk is a charming pedestrian walkway along Roxas Blvd that offers breathtaking sunset views of Manila Bay. It's a great spot to soak in the local atmosphere and enjoy the vibrant surroundings.
name: Baywalk
address: Malate, City Of Manila, 1004 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: A lively, hip area, Makati’s Poblacion is home to backpacker lodgings, as well as the Rockwell Center with its upscale shops, and condo and office buildings. Nightlife centers on Kalayaan Avenue and surrounding streets, with dive bars and live-music venues, plus late-night eateries selling tacos and street food. Housed in a former town hall, Museo Ng Makati traces local history.
detail_description: Poblacion in Makati is a vibrant and trendy neighborhood that offers a mix of history, modern culture, and bustling nightlife. It features backpacker lodgings alongside upscale shops, condo buildings, and office spaces. The area's nightlife scene is centered around Kalayaan Avenue with dive bars, live music venues, and late-night eateries serving up delicious street food.
name: Poblacion
address: Makati City, Metro Manila, Philippines

detail_description: The Cultural Center of the Philippines, designed by the renowned architect Leandro V. Locsin, stands as a testament to his modernist concrete designs. This iconic structure is a significant part of the country's architectural heritage and is a key component of the nation's cultural landscape.
name: Cultural Center of the Philippines
address: HX5M+5CM, Pedro Bukaneg St, Malate, Manila, 1004 Metro Manila, Philippines

detail_description: Robinsons Place Manila is a premier shopping destination in the Philippines, featuring seven storeys filled with premium and luxury brands in fashion, cosmetics, and more. The mall offers a wide range of entertainment options, retail stores, and gaming zones for visitors to enjoy. Additionally, guests can indulge in diverse dining options after a day of shopping. For those seeking unique experiences, the mall also provides bike lessons on its rooftop at The Tracks MNL by the NBO.
name: Robinsons Place Manila
address: Pedro Gil, cor Adriatico St, Ermita, Manila, 1000 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Catholic church containing a revered 17th-century statue of Jesus called the Black Nazarene.
detail_description: The Minor Basilica & National Shrine of Jesus Nazareno, also known as Quiapo Church, is a significant Catholic church in Manila. It houses the revered 17th-century Black Nazarene statue, attracting devoted worshippers who believe in its miraculous powers. The church's iconic architecture, designed by Juan Nakpil, features a spacious dome and imposing belfries.
name: Minor Basilica and National Shrine of Jesus Nazareno - St. John the Baptist Parish (Archdiocese of Manila)
address: 910 Plaza Miranda, Quiapo, Manila, 1001 Metro Manila, Philippines

excerpt: Manila, the capital of the Philippines, is a densely populated bayside city on the island of Luzon, which mixes Spanish colonial architecture with modern skyscrapers. Intramuros, a walled city in colonial times, is the heart of Old Manila. It’s home to the baroque 16th-century San Agustin Church as well as Fort Santiago, a storied citadel and former military prison.
detail_description: Manila, the bustling capital of the Philippines, is a vibrant city that seamlessly blends Spanish colonial architecture with modern skyscrapers. The historic walled city of Intramuros stands as the heart of Old Manila, boasting attractions like the San Agustin Church and Fort Santiago. Whether you're seeking a studio apartment in Quezon City or other vacation rentals in Manila, there are plenty of options to choose from for your stay.
name: City Of Manila
address: Metro Manila, Philippines
